post_text:
The 2019-2020 LHS yearbooks are in!
*Due to Covid-19 restrictions, we ask that you come at designated times for pick up, following all guidelines per MCPH. Email Mrs. George with concerns or to make other arrangements.

Current LHS students who have paid for a yearbook will be called to the Maker Space during AIM on Monday and Tuesday (8/31, 9/1).

Last year’s seniors can pick up their yearbooks at LHS (office) on Wednesday, September 2nd & 9th, between 8-11a.m. & 12:30-2:00 p.m.

If a parent or sibling will be picking up a graduate’s yearbook, please email amy.george@london.k12.oh.us listing your name and who is picking up the yearbook.

If you did not order a 2019-2020 yearbook but would like to purchase one, please email amy.george@london.k12.oh.us. Extra books can be purchased for $60 and will be available once all deliveries have been completed - tentatively the 21st of September. Info to follow.
Thanks!

This Saturday, August 15th, 2020 the HELP House will be distributing backpacks filled with school supplies for students in grades K-5. There also will be a limited supply for students in grades 6-12. The outreach will be from 9 am until noon. No registration is necessary. This year it will be a drive-thru distribution with volunteers practicing social distancing and wearing masks. The HELP House is located at 122 Center Street.

post_text:
The London City School Fine Arts program dedicates itself to providing its students with an annual venue for the various visual and performing arts found within the school district. The venue is called the London City School Fine Arts Festival, and the event will look a little different this time around.

This year, the London City Schools Fine Arts Festival will be a virtual tour featuring artistic compositions, including 2-D and 3-D art and photography from students from all three of the LCS buildings. This platform provides an opportunity to showcase their creative talents, which are typically displayed at the district annual Fine Arts Festival in April.

By incorporating this virtual…

post_text:
On Monday, May 11th the district will be enrolling Kindergarten students for the 2020-21 school year. Your child must be 5 by August 1st to enroll. Please call 740-852-5700, ext 2117 or 2111 to make an appointment.

Only those that have all the required documents will be seen on this date. For the protection of all, we ask that only one parent/guardian attend the appointment. We do not need your child at this time.

To enroll you must bring with you to the appointment:
1. Your photo ID
2. Student's birth certificate (not hospital record)
3. Custody documents (if applicable)
4. Proof of Residency (lease or utility bill)
5. Immunization records
6. Current physical

Maintenance Worker/Custodian, 2nd shift -

The London City School District is seeking qualified applicants for the position(s) of maintenance/custodian.

The district's maintenance/custodial staff provides technical and manual skill in maintaining and cleaning district facilities and equipment. Applicants must be knowledgeable, energetic, reliable, able to successfully pass a background check, and willing to contribute positively as part of a team environment.

Interested applicants should email a letter of introduction and a resume to Dr. Lou Kramer, District Superintendent, at lou.kramer@london.k12.oh.us.

It's Time! Have you called yet?

Dial-A-Carol is an annual student-run service at the University of Illinois at Urbana–Champaign in which students take calls from people asking for a Christmas carol.. It is run out of Snyder Hall, a residence hall in the Ikenberry Commons on campus. Students and staff volunteer to take calls around the clock for one week straight, every year during finals week of every Fall semester. It's only for a limited time...so call soon!!

The London City School District is pleased to announce the return of Mr. Curtis Brooks as a member of the Board of Education. Mr. Brooks previously served on the Board of Education for 10 years (2006-2015) and currently serves as the district’s representative to the Tolles Career and Technical Center Board of Education.

The Board of Education interviewed eight, well qualified applicants for the two-year appointment and making the final selection was difficult. Board members cited Mr. Brooks’ prior experience as a district Board member including stints as both Board President and Vice President as well as his ongoing 14 year…

Message from the Superintendent:

It is with great sadness that I share with you the passing of a London Middle School student, who died by suicide earlier yesterday. Our thoughts and sympathies are with her family and friends.

London teachers and students receive annual training in Signs of Suicide in several different grade levels. Please remember, students who are at risk may be at an even greater risk due to the death of a peer. It is very important, whether you have received this training or not, that If you or someone you know needs help right away, you call the National Suicide Prevention Lifeline at 1-800-273-TALK (8255), call 911, or go to the nearest emergency department.
